name: Tom Glanz 🌟 ⭐
tweet: Whew! UX conference 2/3 this spring is behind me. Thanks to everyone who has joined me recently! - there will be more research tweets down the road! For non-researchers... Back to regularly scheduled Northwest nature, sports, beer, and random tweets for a while 😊

name: Tom Glanz 🌟 ⭐
tweet: This conference was fantastic!! The breadth of topics I walked away being inspired about is impressive. I met some fantastic people, & my biggest question is if there is a @UXRCollective West-coast subsidiary 😉 or can we start one? Looking forward to staying connected! #UXRConf https://twitter.com/UXRCollective/status/1137117115717230594 …

name: Tom Glanz 🌟 ⭐
tweet: Christina Janzer talked about the deeply integrated nature of research teams at Slack - something many orgs can only dream of, I'm sure. But she advocated the power of thinking forward (be a ranger!) and cross-org. I love this mindset and completely agree! #UXRConf pic.twitter.com/sSNBc7fD1Y

name: Tom Glanz 🌟 ⭐
tweet: I walked away from this Slack UXR talk thinking it was the most tactical of the conference. Loved the story telling around the Japanese case study! And Christina's point: "[researchers] get to be the elven rangers.. roam and scout ahead... It's our responsibility" #UXRConf 1/2 https://twitter.com/UXRCollective/status/1137110812596854784 …

name: Tom Glanz 🌟 ⭐
tweet: Great! I'd love to as well; I had a few questions that we didn't have time to get to, so I'll reach out!

name: Tom Glanz 🌟 ⭐

name: Tom Glanz 🌟 ⭐
tweet: I really enjoyed this from @lookback! Even though I might not be building my own company anytime soon (hey who knows), employee burnout is something to absolutely consider & understand. Internal research is a great way to understand and avoid this... #UXRConf 1/2 https://twitter.com/UXRCollective/status/1137107483384848384 …

name: Tom Glanz 🌟 ⭐

name: Tom Glanz 🌟 ⭐

name: Tom Glanz 🌟 ⭐
tweet: I also loved @writingprincess point on EcoTones. We need to find that sweet spot between traditional user research and data science that creates net new value and knowledge. name: Tom Glanz 🌟 ⭐

 & "if you study people, you have to study data". Woo! #UXRConf https://twitter.com/UXRCollective/status/1136694862638702593 …

name: Tom Glanz 🌟 ⭐
tweet: So many times we get asked "well why can't you just ask users about (fill in the tricky construct here... Trust, Simplicity, etc). Groupon researchers explained: 1) there are many conflicting subjective meanings, and 2) humans just don't have the necessary self-insight. #UXRConf

name: Tom Glanz 🌟 ⭐

name: Tom Glanz 🌟 ⭐
tweet: Nope not what I'm saying at all. It was more about the fact that a blown save is a definite loss of a statistic that he had available to him (save). A blown hold is a potential bad stat which isn't something he already had a positive of (that he cared about, a hold)

name: Tom Glanz 🌟 ⭐

name: Tom Glanz 🌟 ⭐
tweet: I think it's 14.7 percent of his appearances. For seager your example would be like 9.5, Zunino is closer to the right idea. But you're assuming it's a random 50. We are saying there is something inherently different about this sample and we want to know why and if it's true

name: Tom Glanz 🌟 ⭐
tweet: A mistake in a tie game maybe gets you a 'L'. a mistake in a save situation, definitely a lost save. Successful season like Diaz has, the difference between a few 'L's is relatively small compared to a potential mlb record of saves. Humans are loss averse (more salient for saves)

name: Tom Glanz 🌟 ⭐
tweet: Fair, didn't know that. Don't think it changes the psychological differences between a save and a hold though as a larger point. I don't think either of us can speak to that with authority though

name: Tom Glanz 🌟 ⭐
